Implement a production-ready Memory System inside the Clinic Management SaaS.

This is not a simple notes feature.
This is a structured + AI-assisted memory layer for patients, reports, doctors, and clinic-level context.

Also ensure the implementation follows:
- clean code
- proper design patterns
- scalability
- modern language features
- production-ready architecture

Project context:
- Backend: Go + PostgreSQL + JWT + multi-tenant
- Frontend: Next.js + TypeScript + Tailwind + shadcn/ui
- Existing modules include:
  - patients
  - doctors
  - appointments
  - reports / attachments
  - AI report analysis (or planned mock/provider abstraction)
  - notifications
  - billing
  - auth + RBAC
- Patient detail page already exists and supports rich expansion

-----------------------------------
GOAL
-----------------------------------

Build a Memory System that allows the application to store, retrieve, and use important contextual knowledge about:
- patients
- doctors
- reports
- clinic-level entities

The system should support:
- structured memory entries
- AI-generated summaries
- searchable memory history
- memory-driven AI assistance later
- patient-facing and clinician-facing insight surfaces

This feature should make the product feel like an AI-assisted clinic platform.

-----------------------------------
CORE MEMORY CONCEPT
-----------------------------------

The memory system should support at least these memory types:

1. Patient Memory
Examples:
- chronic conditions
- allergies
- frequent medications
- important follow-up flags
- preferred doctor
- recurring issues
- no-show behavior
- AI-generated patient summary

2. Report Memory
Examples:
- report summary
- extracted findings
- abnormal indicators
- report tags/classification
- AI Q&A history for a report

3. Doctor Memory
Examples:
- doctor-specific note templates
- preferences for summaries
- specialty-specific patterns
- optional future assistant context

4. Clinic Memory
Examples:
- clinic defaults
- reminder preferences
- operational notes
- future AI context for tenant-wide behavior

-----------------------------------
PHASED IMPLEMENTATION
-----------------------------------

Phase 1 (must implement now):
- memory_entries storage
- patient memory
- report memory
- patient memory tab in frontend
- AI summary storage for patient/report context
- memory list + refresh/regenerate actions

Phase 2 (design for later, do not overbuild now):
- semantic search
- embeddings / pgvector integration
- AI Q&A using retrieved memory context
- doctor memory enhancements

-----------------------------------
BACKEND REQUIREMENTS
-----------------------------------

1) CLEAN ARCHITECTURE

Create a dedicated backend module:

- internal/memory/
  - models.go
  - dto.go
  - repository.go
  - service.go
  - handler.go
  - errors.go
  - summarizer.go
  - search.go

If report AI integration is separate, integrate cleanly without coupling modules badly.

Rules:
- handler -> service -> repository
- no business logic in handlers
- no raw SQL in handlers
- services contain domain logic
- repositories handle data access
- DTOs for API boundaries

-----------------------------------

2) CLEAN CODE

Apply:
- small focused functions
- clear naming
- explicit memory types
- reusable validation
- readable error handling
- no duplicated logic
- clear tenant/entity scoping

-----------------------------------

3) DESIGN PATTERNS

Use appropriate patterns where useful:
- repository pattern for persistence
- service layer for business rules
- provider/strategy abstraction for AI summarization if needed
- mapper functions for DTO/domain conversion
- optional event-driven hooks for auto-refreshing memory after report upload, appointment completion, etc.

Do not overengineer, but keep it extensible.

-----------------------------------

4) SCALABILITY

Design the memory system so it can later support:
- pgvector / embedding search
- semantic retrieval
- memory ranking
- AI assistant over patient/report context
- background summary refresh jobs
- larger memory volumes
- clinic-wide memory and doctor-specific memory

Do not hardcode it as a patient-notes-only feature.

-----------------------------------

5) MODERN LANGUAGE FEATURES

Backend (Go):
- idiomatic modern Go
- context propagation
- proper error wrapping
- typed structs/interfaces
- clean package boundaries
- no global mutable state

Frontend (TypeScript/Next.js):
- strong typing
- typed hooks
- typed API layer
- reusable presentational components
- modern React patterns
- avoid any

-----------------------------------
DATABASE DESIGN
-----------------------------------

Create a migration for memory storage.

Suggested table:
memory_entries
- id UUID PK
- tenant_id UUID NOT NULL
- entity_type VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL
  - patient
  - report
  - doctor
  - clinic
- entity_id UUID NOT NULL
- memory_type VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL
  - summary
  - insight
  - preference
  - alert
  - chat
  - extracted_data
- title VARCHAR(255) NULL
- content TEXT NOT NULL
- metadata JSONB NULL
- source_type VARCHAR(50) NULL
  - system
  - ai
  - user
  - report
  - appointment
- created_by UUID NULL
- created_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW()
- updated_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW()

Indexes:
- (tenant_id, entity_type, entity_id)
- (tenant_id, memory_type)
- maybe GIN index on metadata if useful

Optional future table (design only if helpful, do not overbuild unless clean):
memory_embeddings
- id
- memory_entry_id
- model_name
- embedding/vector
- created_at

-----------------------------------
BACKEND BEHAVIOR
-----------------------------------

Implement backend support for:

1. Create / store memory entries
2. List memory entries for an entity
3. Refresh/regenerate AI summary memory for an entity
4. Store report-derived memory
5. Store patient summary memory

Suggested endpoints:

GET /api/v1/patients/{id}/memory
POST /api/v1/patients/{id}/memory
POST /api/v1/patients/{id}/memory/refresh

GET /api/v1/reports/{id}/memory
POST /api/v1/reports/{id}/memory/refresh

Optional generic endpoint if cleaner:
POST /api/v1/memory/search

All endpoints must:
- enforce tenant isolation
- validate entity ownership
- keep response format consistent with the rest of the API

-----------------------------------
PATIENT SUMMARY MEMORY
-----------------------------------

Implement a basic patient summary memory feature.

Goal:
Store a concise summary of the patient's important context.

Potential sources:
- appointments
- visit notes
- reports
- invoices or attendance patterns if useful

The summary can be:
- AI-generated if provider/mock exists
- or generated by internal summarization logic for now

Examples:
- "Patient has recurring elevated glucose and missed two follow-ups."
- "Patient has allergy history and multiple cardiology follow-ups."

Store this as a memory entry with:
- entity_type = patient
- memory_type = summary
- source_type = ai or system

-----------------------------------
REPORT MEMORY
-----------------------------------

When a report/attachment is analyzed, store a memory entry linked to that report.

Examples:
- summary of report
- extracted key findings
- abnormal values
- report category/type

Store as:
- entity_type = report
- memory_type = summary / extracted_data / insight

If report AI already exists, integrate with it cleanly.
Do not duplicate report analysis logic.

-----------------------------------
AI / SUMMARIZATION ABSTRACTION
-----------------------------------

Use a clean abstraction for memory generation.

Suggested interface idea:
- GeneratePatientSummary(...)
- GenerateReportSummary(...)
- RefreshMemory(...)

If an AI provider abstraction already exists:
- reuse it
- keep it mockable
- do not hardcode one provider in the memory service

If real AI is not available, provide a clean mock or deterministic implementation.

-----------------------------------
AUDIT / TRACEABILITY
-----------------------------------

If audit logs already exist, integrate memory events:
- memory created
- memory refreshed
- report memory generated

Keep it tenant-safe.

-----------------------------------
FRONTEND REQUIREMENTS
-----------------------------------

Add a Memory / AI Insights tab to the patient detail page.

Patient tabs should include:
- Overview
- Appointments
- Billing
- Reports
- Notes
- Memory / AI Insights

Inside the Memory tab:
1. Patient Summary Card
- concise summary
- source label (AI/System)
- last updated time

2. Key Insights List
- memory entries
- titles / content
- type badges (summary / alert / insight / preference)

3. Refresh Summary button
- triggers memory refresh endpoint
- loading state
- success/error feedback

4. Optional Add Memory entry
- manual note-to-memory creation if cleanly useful

Keep the UI clean, professional, and not crowded.

-----------------------------------
FRONTEND ARCHITECTURE
-----------------------------------

Suggested structure:
- features/memory/
  - components/
    - PatientMemoryTab
    - MemorySummaryCard
    - MemoryEntryList
    - MemoryEntryItem
    - RefreshMemoryButton
  - hooks/
    - usePatientMemory
    - useRefreshPatientMemory
    - useCreateMemoryEntry
  - api/
    - memory.ts
  - types.ts
  - schemas.ts

Use:
- TanStack Query
- React Hook Form if needed
- Zod if manual memory creation is supported
- shadcn/ui components

-----------------------------------
FRONTEND UX REQUIREMENTS
-----------------------------------

- clean memory tab
- readable cards and badges
- proper empty state when no memory exists
- skeleton/loading states
- clear source labels
- no dark-on-dark contrast issues
- consistent with the rest of the dashboard
- tenant theme compatibility

Suggested empty state:
- "No memory insights available yet"
- action: "Generate Summary"

-----------------------------------
SEARCH / RETRIEVAL (LIGHT MVP)
-----------------------------------

If cleanly possible in this phase, add a simple text search/filter in memory entries for the current entity.

Do not overbuild vector search yet.

-----------------------------------
PRIVACY / PRODUCT SAFETY
-----------------------------------

Requirements:
- strict tenant isolation
- memory data must never leak across tenants
- AI-generated summaries must not be presented as definitive medical diagnosis
- show disclaimer where appropriate:
  "AI assistance only. Not medical advice."

